  <p class="hero-desc">The Linux file system is not just where files live — it is the entire interface to the OS. Devices, processes, network sockets, and kernel parameters are all represented as files. Understanding this model is the difference between a user who copies commands and an engineer who understands the system.</p>
  <div class="outcomes-grid">
    <div class="outcome-item">Explain the FHS (Filesystem Hierarchy Standard) and what lives where</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Navigate, create, copy, move and delete files and directories</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Read, set and reason about permissions (symbolic and octal)</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Understand hard links, soft links, and inodes</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Use find, locate, and xargs for file operations at scale</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Understand mount points, disk layout, and /proc /sys /dev</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Know special file types: devices, sockets, named pipes</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Debug permission denied, disk full, and missing file errors</div>
  </div>
