<!-- S1: Beginner Intuition -->
<div class="section" id="s1">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🧠</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Beginner Intuition</div><div class="section-num">Section 01 — Simple Mental Model</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="note note-mental">
    <div class="note-label">🧠 Mental Model</div>
    <p>Imagine Linux as a <strong>building</strong>. The entire building is called <code>/</code> (root). Every floor, room, and drawer inside is a directory or file. There is only one building — everything is inside it. Even external hard drives, USB sticks, and network shares get <em>attached</em> (mounted) into a room in this same building. You never leave the building.</p>
  </div>
  <p>This single-tree model is the key difference from Windows, which gives each disk its own letter (C:, D:). In Linux, a USB drive might appear at <code>/media/ubuntu/usb</code> — it is just another directory in the same tree.</p>
  <p>Another crucial mental model: <strong>in Linux, everything is a file</strong>. Your keyboard is a file (<code>/dev/input/event0</code>). Running processes are files (<code>/proc/1234/</code>). The hard disk is a file (<code>/dev/sda</code>). Your network card has a file. This uniform interface is what makes Linux so composable.</p>
  <div class="note note-try">
    <div class="note-label">✅ Try It Now</div>
    <p>Run <code>ls /</code> right now. You are looking at the top of the entire Linux file system. Every directory you see there will mean something by the end of this topic.</p>
  </div>
</div>

