  <h3>The Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS)</h3>
  <p>The FHS is the spec that defines where things live on a Linux system. Every major distro follows it. Knowing this means you can navigate any Linux server you've never seen before.</p>

  <div class="tree">
<span class="tree-dir">/</span>  <span class="tree-desc">← root of the entire filesystem tree</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">bin</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← essential binaries: ls, cat, cp (→ symlink to /usr/bin on modern systems)</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">boot</span>  <span class="tree-desc">← kernel, bootloader (GRUB), initramfs</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">dev</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← device files: disks, terminals, random, null</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">etc</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← system configuration files (text-based, editable)</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">home</span>  <span class="tree-desc">← user home directories: /home/alice, /home/bob</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">lib</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← shared libraries for /bin and /sbin binaries</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">media</span> <span class="tree-desc">← auto-mount point for removable media (USB, CD)</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">mnt</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← manual temporary mount points</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">opt</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← optional third-party software packages</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">proc</span>  <span class="tree-desc">← virtual fs: running process info, kernel state (not on disk!)</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">root</span>  <span class="tree-desc">← root user's home directory (separate from /home)</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">run</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← runtime data (PIDs, sockets) — cleared on reboot</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">sbin</span>  <span class="tree-desc">← system binaries for root: fdisk, mount, ifconfig</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">srv</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← data for services: /srv/www, /srv/ftp</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">sys</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← virtual fs: kernel/hardware state, tunable parameters</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">tmp</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← temporary files (cleared on reboot — do NOT store important data here)</span>
├── <span class="tree-dir">usr</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← user programs and data (read-only in ideal setups)</span>
│   ├── <span class="tree-dir">bin</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← most user commands: vim, python3, git</span>
│   ├── <span class="tree-dir">lib</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← shared libraries for /usr/bin programs</span>
│   ├── <span class="tree-dir">local</span> <span class="tree-desc">← locally compiled software (not from package manager)</span>
│   └── <span class="tree-dir">share</span> <span class="tree-desc">← arch-independent data: man pages, docs, icons</span>
└── <span class="tree-dir">var</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← variable data that grows: logs, caches, mail, databases</span>
    ├── <span class="tree-dir">log</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← system and application logs</span>
    ├── <span class="tree-dir">lib</span>   <span class="tree-desc">← persistent app state (databases, package manager state)</span>
    └── <span class="tree-dir">cache</span> <span class="tree-desc">← application caches (safe to delete)</span>
  </div>

  <h3>Absolute vs Relative Paths</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Type</th><th>Starts with</th><th>Example</th><th>Means</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Absolute</td><td><code>/</code></td><td><code>/home/ubuntu/file.txt</code></td><td>Full path from root — always unambiguous</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Relative</td><td>anything else</td><td><code>Documents/file.txt</code></td><td>Relative to your current directory</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Home shortcut</td><td><code>~</code></td><td><code>~/Documents/file.txt</code></td><td>Expands to your home directory</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Current dir</td><td><code>./</code></td><td><code>./script.sh</code></td><td>Explicitly the current directory</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Parent dir</td><td><code>../</code></td><td><code>../config.txt</code></td><td>One directory up</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>File Types in Linux</h3>
  <p>Linux has more than just regular files and directories. The first character of <code>ls -la</code> output tells you the type:</p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Symbol</th><th>Type</th><th>Example</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>-</code></td><td>Regular file</td><td><code>config.txt</code></td><td>Text, binary, scripts, anything</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>d</code></td><td>Directory</td><td><code>/home/ubuntu</code></td><td>A container of files</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>l</code></td><td>Symbolic link</td><td><code>/bin → /usr/bin</code></td><td>A pointer to another file/dir</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>b</code></td><td>Block device</td><td><code>/dev/sda</code></td><td>Hard disks, USB drives</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>c</code></td><td>Character device</td><td><code>/dev/tty</code></td><td>Terminals, serial ports</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>p</code></td><td>Named pipe (FIFO)</td><td><code>/tmp/mypipe</code></td><td>IPC between processes</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>s</code></td><td>Socket</td><td><code>/var/run/docker.sock</code></td><td>Network/IPC communication</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>Linux File Permissions — The Core Model</h3>
  <p>Every file has three sets of permissions for three classes of user:</p>

  <div class="perm-demo" style="padding: 16px 20px; background: var(--surface2); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border); margin: 12px 0; font-size: 22px; letter-spacing: 2px;">
    <span class="p-type">-</span><span class="p-owner">rwx</span><span class="p-group">r-x</span><span class="p-other">r--</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;
    <span style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); letter-spacing: 0;">← type | owner | group | others</span>
  </div>

  <div class="perm-grid">
    <div class="perm-cell"><div class="perm-who">Owner (u)</div><div class="perm-bits owner">rwx</div><div class="perm-octal">7</div></div>
    <div class="perm-cell"><div class="perm-who">Group (g)</div><div class="perm-bits group">r-x</div><div class="perm-octal">5</div></div>
    <div class="perm-cell"><div class="perm-who">Others (o)</div><div class="perm-bits other">r--</div><div class="perm-octal">4</div></div>
    <div class="perm-cell" style="border-top:1px solid var(--border)"><div class="perm-who">r = read</div><div class="perm-bits" style="color:var(--text2); font-size:15px">value: 4</div></div>
    <div class="perm-cell" style="border-top:1px solid var(--border)"><div class="perm-who">w = write</div><div class="perm-bits" style="color:var(--text2); font-size:15px">value: 2</div></div>
    <div class="perm-cell" style="border-top:1px solid var(--border)"><div class="perm-who">x = execute</div><div class="perm-bits" style="color:var(--text2); font-size:15px">value: 1</div></div>
  </div>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Reading octal: add up the values for each set</span>
<span class="cm"># rwx = 4+2+1 = 7   r-x = 4+0+1 = 5   r-- = 4+0+0 = 4</span>
<span class="cm"># So -rwxr-xr-- = 754</span>

<span class="cm"># Common permission values you'll see daily:</span>
<span class="cm"># 644 (-rw-r--r--)  regular file, owner can write, others read only</span>
<span class="cm"># 755 (-rwxr-xr-x)  script/binary, everyone can execute</span>
<span class="cm"># 700 (-rwx------)  private script, only owner can access</span>
<span class="cm"># 600 (-rw-------)  private file (SSH keys MUST be this)</span>
<span class="cm"># 777 (-rwxrwxrwx)  everyone full access — dangerous, almost never correct</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Inodes — The real identity of a file</h3>
  <p>Every file is represented by an <strong>inode</strong> — a data structure stored on disk that contains all metadata about the file: permissions, owner, size, timestamps, and pointers to the actual data blocks. The filename is just a label attached to an inode via a directory entry. The inode number is the file's real identity.</p>

  <pre><code><span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-li</span> /etc/passwd
<span class="cm"># 131073 -rw-r--r-- 1 root root 2847 Jan 15 09:22 /etc/passwd</span>
<span class="cm"># 131073 = inode number</span>

<span class="cn">stat</span> /etc/passwd        <span class="cm"># full inode info: size, blocks, inode num, all timestamps</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S3: Commands -->
<div class="section" id="s3">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">⚙️</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Commands & Syntax</div><div class="section-num">Section 03 — Every essential file system command</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Creating, copying, moving, deleting</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Create</span>
<span class="cn">touch</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span>              <span class="cm"># create empty file (or update timestamp if exists)</span>
<span class="cn">mkdir</span> <span class="st">mydir</span>                 <span class="cm"># create directory</span>
<span class="cn">mkdir</span> <span class="fl">-p</span> <span class="st">a/b/c/d</span>           <span class="cm"># create entire path at once (no error if exists)</span>
<span class="cn">mkdir</span> <span class="fl">-m 750</span> <span class="st">securedir</span>     <span class="cm"># create with specific permissions</span>

<span class="cm"># Copy</span>
<span class="cn">cp</span> <span class="st">file.txt copy.txt</span>        <span class="cm"># copy file</span>
<span class="cn">cp</span> <span class="fl">-r</span> <span class="st">dir1/ dir2/</span>          <span class="cm"># copy directory recursively</span>
<span class="cn">cp</span> <span class="fl">-p</span> <span class="st">file.txt backup.txt</span>  <span class="cm"># preserve: timestamps, permissions, owner</span>
<span class="cn">cp</span> <span class="fl">-a</span> <span class="st">dir1/ dir2/</span>          <span class="cm"># archive mode: recursive + preserve everything</span>
<span class="cn">cp</span> <span class="fl">-v</span> <span class="st">file.txt dest/</span>       <span class="cm"># verbose: show what's being copied</span>

<span class="cm"># Move / Rename</span>
<span class="cn">mv</span> <span class="st">file.txt newname.txt</span>    <span class="cm"># rename file</span>
<span class="cn">mv</span> <span class="st">file.txt /tmp/</span>          <span class="cm"># move to /tmp directory</span>
<span class="cn">mv</span> <span class="fl">-i</span> <span class="st">file.txt dest/</span>       <span class="cm"># interactive: ask before overwriting</span>
<span class="cn">mv</span> <span class="fl">-n</span> <span class="st">file.txt dest/</span>       <span class="cm"># no clobber: never overwrite</span>

<span class="cm"># Delete</span>
<span class="cn">rm</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span>                 <span class="cm"># delete file</span>
<span class="cn">rm</span> <span class="fl">-i</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span>             <span class="cm"># ask before deleting (safer)</span>
<span class="cn">rm</span> <span class="fl">-r</span> <span class="st">mydir/</span>               <span class="cm"># delete directory recursively</span>
<span class="cn">rm</span> <span class="fl">-rf</span> <span class="st">mydir/</span>              <span class="cm"># force delete, no questions asked (dangerous!)</span>
<span class="cn">rmdir</span> <span class="st">emptydir</span>             <span class="cm"># remove directory ONLY if empty (safer than rm -r)</span></code></pre>

  <div class="note note-warn">
    <div class="note-label">⚠️ The most dangerous command in Linux</div>
    <p><code>rm -rf /</code> deletes the entire filesystem. Modern systems protect against this with <code>--no-preserve-root</code> being required, but <code>rm -rf /*</code> still works. Always double-check paths before using <code>-rf</code>. Use <code>echo rm -rf path</code> to do a dry run first.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Permissions commands</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># chmod — change file permissions</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">755</span> <span class="st">script.sh</span>           <span class="cm"># octal: rwxr-xr-x</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">644</span> <span class="st">config.txt</span>          <span class="cm"># octal: rw-r--r--</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="fl">u+x</span> <span class="st">script.sh</span>          <span class="cm"># symbolic: add execute for owner</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="fl">g-w</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span>           <span class="cm"># symbolic: remove write from group</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="fl">o=r</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span>           <span class="cm"># symbolic: set others to read only</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="fl">a+r</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span>           <span class="cm"># a = all (u+g+o): add read for everyone</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="fl">-R</span> <span class="st">755</span> <span class="st">mydir/</span>          <span class="cm"># recursive: apply to all files in directory</span>

<span class="cm"># chown — change file owner and group</span>
<span class="cn">chown</span> <span class="st">ubuntu file.txt</span>        <span class="cm"># change owner to ubuntu</span>
<span class="cn">chown</span> <span class="st">ubuntu:webteam</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span><span class="cm"> # change owner AND group</span>
<span class="cn">chown</span> <span class="fl">:webteam</span> <span class="st">file.txt</span>      <span class="cm"># change group only (same as chgrp)</span>
<span class="cn">chown</span> <span class="fl">-R</span> <span class="st">www-data:www-data</span> <span class="st">/var/www</span> <span class="cm"># recursive (common for web apps)</span>

<span class="cm"># chgrp — change group only</span>
<span class="cn">chgrp</span> <span class="st">developers file.txt</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Links: hard links and symbolic links</h3>
  <div class="note note-mental">
    <div class="note-label">🧠 Mental Model</div>
    <p><strong>Hard link</strong> = another name pointing to the same inode (same data on disk). Delete one name — data still exists via the other. <strong>Symbolic link</strong> = a shortcut file that contains a path. Delete the target — the symlink breaks (dangles). Think of hard links as aliases and symlinks as shortcuts.</p>
  </div>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Hard links</span>
<span class="cn">ln</span> <span class="st">original.txt hardlink.txt</span>  <span class="cm"># create hard link</span>
<span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-li</span> <span class="st">original.txt hardlink.txt</span> <span class="cm"># both show the SAME inode number</span>
<span class="cm"># Hard links: can't cross filesystems, can't link directories</span>

<span class="cm"># Symbolic links</span>
<span class="cn">ln</span> <span class="fl">-s</span> <span class="st">/etc/nginx/sites-available/mysite</span> <span class="st">/etc/nginx/sites-enabled/mysite</span>
<span class="cm"># ↑ Real production pattern: enable nginx sites via symlinks</span>
<span class="cn">ln</span> <span class="fl">-s</span> <span class="st">/usr/bin/python3</span> <span class="st">/usr/local/bin/python</span>
<span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-la</span> <span class="st">/etc/nginx/sites-enabled/</span>
<span class="cm"># lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root  34 Jan 15 mysite -> /etc/nginx/sites-available/mysite</span>
<span class="cm"># l = symlink, -> shows the target</span>

<span class="cm"># Check and repair symlinks</span>
<span class="cn">readlink</span> <span class="fl">-f</span> <span class="st">mysymlink</span>         <span class="cm"># resolve to final real path</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/etc</span> <span class="fl">-xtype l</span>           <span class="cm"># find all broken symlinks</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Finding files</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># find — powerful, always available, works on live filesystem</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/home</span> <span class="fl">-name</span> <span class="st">"*.log"</span>     <span class="cm"># find by name pattern</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/</span> <span class="fl">-name</span> <span class="st">"passwd"</span> <span class="fl">-type f</span> <span class="cm"># by name AND type (f=file, d=dir, l=link)</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/log</span> <span class="fl">-mtime -1</span>      <span class="cm"># modified in the last 1 day</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/log</span> <span class="fl">-mtime +30</span>     <span class="cm"># modified more than 30 days ago</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/home</span> <span class="fl">-size +100M</span>       <span class="cm"># files larger than 100MB</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/</span> <span class="fl">-perm 777</span>             <span class="cm"># files with exactly 777 permissions</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/</span> <span class="fl">-user ubuntu</span>          <span class="cm"># files owned by ubuntu</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/tmp</span> <span class="fl">-name</span> <span class="st">"*.tmp"</span> <span class="fl">-delete</span> <span class="cm"># find AND delete matching files</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/etc</span> <span class="fl">-name</span> <span class="st">"*.conf"</span> <span class="fl">-exec grep -l "listen" {} \;</span> <span class="cm"># find then run command on each</span>

<span class="cm"># xargs — feed find results into another command efficiently</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/log</span> <span class="fl">-name</span> <span class="st">"*.log"</span> <span class="fl">-mtime +30</span> | <span class="cn">xargs</span> <span class="cn">rm</span> <span class="fl">-f</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/home</span> <span class="fl">-name</span> <span class="st">"*.txt"</span> | <span class="cn">xargs</span> <span class="cn">grep</span> <span class="fl">-l</span> <span class="st">"TODO"</span>

<span class="cm"># locate — searches a pre-built index (much faster, but may be stale)</span>
<span class="cn">locate</span> <span class="st">nginx.conf</span>            <span class="cm"># instant search from index</span>
<span class="cn">updatedb</span>                     <span class="cm"># refresh the index (run as root)</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Disk usage and space</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cn">df</span> <span class="fl">-h</span>                         <span class="cm"># disk free: show all mounted filesystems + usage</span>
<span class="cn">df</span> <span class="fl">-i</span>                         <span class="cm"># inode usage (can be full even if disk has space!)</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-sh</span> <span class="st">/var/log</span>              <span class="cm"># disk usage: total size of directory</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-sh</span> <span class="st">/var/log/*</span>            <span class="cm"># size of each item inside /var/log</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-sh</span> <span class="st">/var/log/*</span> | <span class="cn">sort</span> <span class="fl">-rh</span> | <span class="cn">head</span> <span class="fl">10</span>  <span class="cm"># top 10 space hogs</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-d 1 -h</span> <span class="st">/var</span>             <span class="cm"># depth-1: show immediate children only</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Special permission bits</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># SetUID (SUID) — run as the file's owner, not the caller</span>
<span class="cm"># Example: /usr/bin/passwd is owned by root, has SUID set</span>
<span class="cm"># So any user can change their password (it briefly runs as root)</span>
<span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-la</span> <span class="st">/usr/bin/passwd</span>
<span class="cm"># -rwsr-xr-x root root ... (s in owner execute = SUID set)</span>

<span class="cm"># SetGID (SGID) — files created in directory inherit group</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">g+s</span> <span class="st">shared_dir/</span>       <span class="cm"># new files get the dir's group, not creator's</span>

<span class="cm"># Sticky bit — only owner can delete their own files</span>
<span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-la</span> <span class="st">/tmp</span>
<span class="cm"># drwxrwxrwt ... (t at end = sticky bit)</span>
<span class="cm"># Anyone can write to /tmp but only YOU can delete YOUR files</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">+t</span> <span class="st">shared_dir/</span>        <span class="cm"># set sticky bit</span></code></pre>
</div>

