<!-- S5: Under the Hood -->
<div class="section" id="s5">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔬</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Under the Hood</div><div class="section-num">Section 05 — How the filesystem really works</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note note-hood">
    <div class="note-label">🔬 Under the Hood</div>
    <p>Understanding the internals explains behaviours that otherwise seem mysterious — like why deleting a file doesn't immediately free disk space, or why you can rename a file while it's being written to.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Inodes, data blocks, and the VFS</h3>
  <p>A filesystem on disk consists of: a <strong>superblock</strong> (filesystem metadata), an <strong>inode table</strong> (one inode per file), and <strong>data blocks</strong> (actual file content). When the kernel opens a file by name, it traverses directory entries to find the inode number, reads the inode for permissions and block locations, then reads the data blocks.</p>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># An inode contains:</span>
<span class="cm"># - file type and permissions</span>
<span class="cm"># - owner UID and GID</span>
<span class="cm"># - size in bytes</span>
<span class="cm"># - timestamps: atime (access), mtime (modify content), ctime (change inode)</span>
<span class="cm"># - hard link count</span>
<span class="cm"># - pointers to data blocks on disk</span>
<span class="cm"># What it does NOT contain: the filename!</span>

<span class="cn">stat</span> /etc/hostname
<span class="cm"># File: /etc/hostname</span>
<span class="cm"># Size: 8            Blocks: 8          IO Block: 4096   regular file</span>
<span class="cm"># Device: 802h/2050d   Inode: 131152      Links: 1</span>
<span class="cm"># Access: (0644/-rw-r--r--)  Uid: (    0/    root)   Gid: (    0/    root)</span>
<span class="cm"># Access: 2024-01-15 09:22:01.000000000 +0000</span>
<span class="cm"># Modify: 2024-01-15 09:22:01.000000000 +0000</span>
<span class="cm"># Change: 2024-01-15 09:22:01.000000000 +0000</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Why deleted files don't free space immediately</h3>
  <p>When you run <code>rm file.txt</code>, the kernel decrements the inode's <strong>hard link count</strong> by 1. If it reaches 0 AND no process has the file open, the inode and data blocks are marked free. But if a process still has the file open (like a log writer), the data stays on disk until that process closes it. This is why <code>df -h</code> still shows a full disk after deleting a log file — the writing process still has it open.</p>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Diagnose "disk full but no files found":</span>
<span class="cn">lsof</span> <span class="st">+L1</span>   <span class="cm"># show open files with zero link count (deleted but still open)</span>
<span class="cm"># Kill the process OR truncate the file to free space immediately:</span>
<span class="cn">truncate</span> <span class="fl">-s 0</span> <span class="st">/var/log/myapp.log</span>  <span class="cm"># set file to 0 bytes without restart</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Mount points and the VFS</h3>
  <p>The <strong>VFS (Virtual Filesystem Switch)</strong> is a kernel abstraction layer. All filesystems — ext4, xfs, btrfs, tmpfs, nfs, proc, sysfs — present the same API to the kernel. You interact with all of them identically. A <strong>mount</strong> operation grafts the root of one filesystem onto a directory in the main tree.</p>

  <pre><code><span class="cn">mount</span>                          <span class="cm"># show all mounted filesystems</span>
<span class="cn">cat</span> /proc/mounts               <span class="cm"># kernel's live view of mounts</span>
<span class="cn">findmnt</span>                        <span class="cm"># tree view of mount points (modern, clear)</span>

<span class="cm"># Mount a disk temporarily:</span>
<span class="cn">mount</span> <span class="st">/dev/sdb1 /mnt/data</span>     <span class="cm"># mount device at /mnt/data</span>
<span class="cn">umount</span> <span class="st">/mnt/data</span>              <span class="cm"># unmount (fails if in use — "target is busy")</span>

<span class="cm"># Persistent mounts go in /etc/fstab:</span>
<span class="cm"># /dev/sdb1   /data   ext4   defaults   0   2</span>
<span class="cm"># device      mount   type   options   dump fsck-order</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Common filesystem types</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Filesystem</th><th>Use Case</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>ext4</code></td><td>Default Linux disk FS</td><td>Reliable, mature, journaled. Most common.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>xfs</code></td><td>Large files, databases</td><td>Default on RHEL/CentOS. High performance.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>btrfs</code></td><td>Snapshots, RAID</td><td>Modern, copy-on-write. Default on OpenSUSE.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>tmpfs</code></td><td>RAM-based temp storage</td><td><code>/tmp</code> and <code>/run</code> are usually tmpfs.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>proc</code></td><td>Process/kernel info</td><td>Virtual — nothing on disk</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>sysfs</code></td><td>Kernel/hardware state</td><td>Virtual — mounted at /sys</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>nfs</code></td><td>Network file shares</td><td>Remote filesystems mounted locally</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>vfat</code></td><td>USB drives, EFI partition</td><td>No Unix permissions — everything is 777</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<!-- S6: Real World -->
<div class="section" id="s6">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🏭</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Real-World Usage</div><div class="section-num">Section 06 — Daily filesystem tasks in production</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note note-real">
    <div class="note-label">🏭 Real-World Usage</div>
    <p>These are tasks a DevOps engineer performs on real servers weekly.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Investigating disk space issues</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Step 1: Which filesystem is full?</span>
<span class="cn">df</span> <span class="fl">-h</span>

<span class="cm"># Step 2: Find which directory is largest</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-d1 -h</span> <span class="st">/var</span> | <span class="cn">sort</span> <span class="fl">-rh</span> | <span class="cn">head</span> <span class="fl">10</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-d1 -h</span> <span class="st">/var/log</span> | <span class="cn">sort</span> <span class="fl">-rh</span> | <span class="cn">head</span> <span class="fl">10</span>

<span class="cm"># Step 3: Find individual large files</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/log</span> <span class="fl">-type f -size +100M</span>

<span class="cm"># Step 4: Check for deleted-but-open files eating space</span>
<span class="cn">lsof</span> <span class="st">+L1</span> | <span class="cn">grep</span> <span class="st">deleted</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Setting up a shared directory for a team</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Create shared dir with SetGID so all files get shared group</span>
<span class="cn">mkdir</span> <span class="st">/opt/project</span>
<span class="cn">chown</span> <span class="st">root:devteam /opt/project</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">2775</span> <span class="st">/opt/project</span>         <span class="cm"># 2=setgid, 775=rwxrwxr-x</span>
<span class="cm"># Now any devteam member's new files auto-inherit 'devteam' group</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Deploying apps with correct permissions</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Web app deployment pattern</span>
<span class="cn">chown</span> <span class="fl">-R</span> <span class="st">www-data:www-data /var/www/myapp</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/www/myapp</span> <span class="fl">-type d -exec</span> <span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">755</span> <span class="st">{}</span> <span class="st">\;</span>  <span class="cm"># dirs: executable</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/www/myapp</span> <span class="fl">-type f -exec</span> <span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">644</span> <span class="st">{}</span> <span class="st">\;</span>  <span class="cm"># files: no execute</span>
<span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">755</span> <span class="st">/var/www/myapp/scripts/*.sh</span>               <span class="cm"># re-add execute to scripts</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Managing log rotation manually</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Rotate a log without restarting the service (zero-downtime)</span>
<span class="cn">mv</span> <span class="st">/var/log/myapp.log /var/log/myapp.log.$(date +%Y%m%d)</span>
<span class="cn">gzip</span> <span class="st">/var/log/myapp.log.$(date +%Y%m%d)</span>
<span class="cn">kill</span> <span class="fl">-HUP</span> <span class="st">$(cat /var/run/myapp.pid)</span>  <span class="cm"># signal app to reopen log file</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S7: Modern vs Legacy -->
<div class="section" id="s7">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔄</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Modern vs Legacy Tools</div><div class="section-num">Section 07 — What changed and why it matters</div></div>
  </div>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Legacy</th><th>Modern</th><th>Reason to switch</th><th>When to use legacy</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>find + rm</code></td><td><code>find -delete</code></td><td>Atomic, no xargs quoting issues</td><td>Complex pipelines</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>df / du</code></td><td><code>duf</code>, <code>ncdu</code></td><td>Interactive, coloured, treemap</td><td>Scripts, remote servers</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>ls -la</code></td><td><code>eza -la</code></td><td>Git status, icons, color coding</td><td>Always know ls first</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>cat</code></td><td><code>bat</code></td><td>Syntax highlight, git diff, line numbers</td><td>Scripts, pipes</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>locate</code></td><td><code>fd</code></td><td>Respects .gitignore, faster, sane defaults</td><td>Large filesystem sweeps</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>chmod -R 755</code></td><td><code>chmod -R u=rwX,go=rX</code></td><td>Capital X = execute only for dirs, not files</td><td>Simple single files</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="note note-senior">
    <div class="note-label">💡 Senior Engineer Insight</div>
    <p>The capital <code>X</code> in <code>chmod</code> is something many miss: <code>chmod -R 755 /dir</code> makes ALL files executable, including config files and images. <code>chmod -R u=rwX,go=rX /dir</code> only sets the execute bit on items that are already directories or already executable. This is the correct pattern for recursive permission setting on web application directories.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S8: Beginner Mistakes -->
<div class="section" id="s8">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">⚠️</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Common Beginner Mistakes</div><div class="section-num">Section 08</div></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Using <code>chmod 777</code> as a "fix":</strong> When something fails with permission denied, beginners often chmod 777. This creates a security hole. The correct approach is to understand <em>why</em> access is denied and fix the minimal necessary permission.</li>
    <li><strong>Confusing <code>rm -rf</code> with wildcards:</strong> <code>rm -rf /home/ubuntu/ *</code> (note the space) deletes the directory AND then tries to delete everything in the current directory. No space: <code>rm -rf /home/ubuntu/*</code> deletes contents only.</li>
    <li><strong>Not using <code>-p</code> with mkdir:</strong> <code>mkdir a/b/c</code> fails if <code>a/b</code> doesn't exist. Use <code>mkdir -p a/b/c</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Absolute vs relative confusion with symlinks:</strong> <code>ln -s config.txt link</code> creates a relative symlink — it breaks if you move <code>link</code> to another directory. Use absolute paths in symlinks unless you know what you're doing.</li>
    <li><strong>Editing files in <code>/tmp</code> as persistent storage:</strong> <code>/tmp</code> is cleared on reboot. Never store anything important there.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring inode exhaustion:</strong> A disk can be "full" with 0 free inodes even with GB of free space. This happens with millions of tiny files (like log entries). Always check both <code>df -h</code> AND <code>df -i</code>.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- S9: Production Mistakes -->
<div class="section" id="s9">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🏗️</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Common Production Mistakes</div><div class="section-num">Section 09</div></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Recursive chown/chmod on <code>/</code>:</strong> Running <code>chown -R www-data /</code> instead of <code>chown -R www-data /var/www</code> breaks the entire system. Always double check the path before <code>-R</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Breaking SUID on <code>/usr/bin/passwd</code>:</strong> Recursive <code>chmod -R</code> on system directories removes SUID bits. Users lose the ability to change their own passwords. Check with <code>ls -la /usr/bin/passwd</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Typo in /etc/fstab:</strong> A bad entry in <code>/etc/fstab</code> prevents the system from booting. Always test with <code>mount -a</code> before rebooting.</li>
    <li><strong>Not accounting for filesystem type on FAT volumes:</strong> Copying files to a USB drive (vfat) silently drops all Unix permissions, symlinks, and ownership. Files appear to copy fine then cause errors when used.</li>
    <li><strong>Relying on atime:</strong> Many systems mount with <code>noatime</code> for performance. Don't use file access time as a proxy for "was this file recently used" in production scripts.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- S10: Debug Workflow -->
<div class="section" id="s10">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🛠</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Debugging Workflow</div><div class="section-num">Section 10 — Systematic approach to filesystem problems</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note note-debug">
    <div class="note-label">🛠 Filesystem Troubleshooting Checklist</div>
    <p>When you hit a filesystem error, work through this order.</p>
  </div>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># "Permission denied"</span>
<span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-la</span> <span class="st">thefile</span>            <span class="cm"># who owns it, what permissions?</span>
<span class="cn">id</span>                        <span class="cm"># what user/groups am I?</span>
<span class="cn">namei</span> <span class="fl">-l</span> <span class="st">/path/to/file</span>   <span class="cm"># check permissions on EVERY component of path</span>
<span class="cm"># namei is critical — a parent dir with no execute bit blocks access to children</span>

<span class="cm"># "No space left on device"</span>
<span class="cn">df</span> <span class="fl">-h</span>                     <span class="cm"># which partition is full?</span>
<span class="cn">df</span> <span class="fl">-i</span>                     <span class="cm"># also check inodes</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-d1 -h</span> <span class="st">/var</span> | <span class="cn">sort</span> <span class="fl">-rh</span> | <span class="cn">head</span>  <span class="cm"># drill down to culprit</span>
<span class="cn">lsof</span> <span class="st">+L1</span>                 <span class="cm"># deleted-but-open files</span>

<span class="cm"># "No such file or directory" (but you can see it with ls)</span>
<span class="cn">file</span> <span class="st">thefile</span>              <span class="cm"># is it a broken symlink?</span>
<span class="cn">readlink</span> <span class="fl">-f</span> <span class="st">thefile</span>       <span class="cm"># where does the symlink point?</span>
<span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-la</span> <span class="st">thefile</span>            <span class="cm"># check type character (l = symlink)</span>

<span class="cm"># Corrupted filesystem (after crash)</span>
<span class="cn">dmesg</span> | <span class="cn">grep</span> <span class="fl">-i</span> <span class="st">"error\|fault\|corrupt"</span>   <span class="cm"># check kernel messages</span>
<span class="cm"># Boot to recovery mode and run:</span>
<span class="cm"># fsck /dev/sda1  — NEVER run fsck on a mounted partition!</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S11: Security -->
<div class="section" id="s11">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔐</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Security Considerations</div><div class="section-num">Section 11</div></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>SSH keys must be 600:</strong> <code>~/.ssh/id_rsa</code> (private key) must be <code>-rw-------</code>. OpenSSH refuses to use keys that are world or group readable.</li>
    <li><strong>World-writable files are a red flag:</strong> <code>find / -perm -002 -not -path "/proc/*" -not -path "/sys/*"</code> finds them. Any file writable by others could be modified by any user.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit SUID/SGID binaries:</strong> <code>find / -perm /6000 -type f 2>/dev/null</code>. Unexpected SUID binaries are a common privilege escalation vector.</li>
    <li><strong>The <code>/tmp</code> symlink attack:</strong> Predictable temp file names in world-writable directories can be exploited. Scripts should use <code>mktemp</code> for secure temp file creation.</li>
    <li><strong>Sensitive files in wrong locations:</strong> Config files with credentials should live in <code>/etc</code> or app config dirs with <code>600</code> or <code>640</code> permissions, not in web-accessible paths.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="note note-sec">
    <div class="note-label">🔐 Security Audit Commands</div>
    <p><code>find / -perm /4000 -type f 2&gt;/dev/null</code> — find all SUID files. <code>find / -perm -0002 -type f 2&gt;/dev/null</code> — find world-writable files. Run these on any new server as part of your baseline security check.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S12: Performance -->
<div class="section" id="s12">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🚀</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Performance Considerations</div><div class="section-num">Section 12</div></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong><code>noatime</code> mount option:</strong> By default, reading a file updates its access timestamp — a write on every read. Mount with <code>noatime</code> or <code>relatime</code> in <code>/etc/fstab</code> to eliminate this overhead. Standard on high-traffic servers.</li>
    <li><strong>Inode count on creation:</strong> If your application creates millions of small files, choose a filesystem with a larger inode table, or use a directory structure to distribute files (e.g., hash-sharded directories).</li>
    <li><strong><code>find</code> on large trees is slow:</strong> For repeated lookups, <code>locate</code> (pre-indexed) is orders of magnitude faster. For one-off searches, <code>fd</code> is faster than <code>find</code> due to parallel traversal.</li>
    <li><strong>Disk I/O scheduling:</strong> SSDs benefit from the <code>none</code> or <code>mq-deadline</code> I/O scheduler. HDDs benefit from <code>cfq</code> or <code>bfq</code>. Check with <code>cat /sys/block/sda/queue/scheduler</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>tmpfs for high-frequency temp files:</strong> If your app writes many small temp files, consider pointing its temp dir to a <code>tmpfs</code> mount (RAM-backed). No disk I/O at all.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- S13: Best Practices -->
<div class="section" id="s13">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">💡</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Best Practices — Senior Level</div><div class="section-num">Section 13</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="senior-block">
    <h4>How a senior engineer thinks about the filesystem</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>They always test <code>rm</code> commands with <code>ls</code> first — same flags, same path. Run <code>ls -la /some/path/*.log</code>, verify output, then run <code>rm</code>.</li>
      <li>They use <code>chmod u=rwX,go=rX</code> instead of blanket <code>chmod -R 755</code> — preserves execute only where appropriate.</li>
      <li>They never store credentials in world-readable locations. Config files with secrets get <code>chmod 600</code> immediately after creation.</li>
      <li>They always run <code>mount -a</code> and <code>df -h</code> after editing <code>/etc/fstab</code> — before rebooting.</li>
      <li>They use <code>namei -l /path</code> when a permission error is confusing — it shows every step of the path resolution.</li>
      <li>They know that <code>mv</code> within the same filesystem is instant (just updates directory entries). <code>mv</code> across filesystems copies then deletes — can be slow for large files.</li>
      <li>They check both <code>df -h</code> AND <code>df -i</code> during disk space incidents — both can fill up independently.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Safe recursive permission fix for a web app directory:</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/www/myapp</span> <span class="fl">-type d -exec</span> <span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">755</span> <span class="st">{}</span> <span class="st">\;</span>
<span class="cn">find</span> <span class="st">/var/www/myapp</span> <span class="fl">-type f -exec</span> <span class="cn">chmod</span> <span class="st">644</span> <span class="st">{}</span> <span class="st">\;</span>
<span class="cm"># Handles files and directories separately — much safer than chmod -R 755</span>

<span class="cm"># Verify before rebooting after fstab edit:</span>
<span class="cn">mount</span> <span class="fl">-a</span> && <span class="cn">df</span> <span class="fl">-h</span> && echo <span class="st">"fstab looks good"</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S14: Incidents -->
<div class="section" id="s14">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔥</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Real Incident Scenarios</div><div class="section-num">Section 14</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="incident">
    <div class="incident-label">🚨 Production Incident — Simulation</div>
    <h4>Disk Full — Service Down at 3am</h4>
    <p><strong>Alert:</strong> "Database write errors. Service returning 500s."</p>
    <p><strong>Diagnosis chain:</strong></p>
    <pre style="margin:8px 0"><code><span class="cn">df</span> <span class="fl">-h</span>            <span class="cm"># /var partition at 100%</span>
<span class="cn">du</span> <span class="fl">-d1 -h</span> <span class="st">/var</span> | <span class="cn">sort</span> <span class="fl">-rh</span> | <span class="cn">head</span>  <span class="cm"># /var/log is 40GB</span>
<span class="cn">ls</span> <span class="fl">-lh</span> <span class="st">/var/log/myapp*</span>  <span class="cm"># myapp.log is 38GB — no log rotation configured!</span>
<span class="cn">lsof</span> <span class="st">+L1</span>          <span class="cm"># no deleted files open</span></code></pre>
    <p><strong>Immediate fix:</strong> <code>truncate -s 0 /var/log/myapp.log</code> — zeroes the file without restart. Service recovers.</p>
    <p><strong>Root cause:</strong> Application logging at DEBUG level in production with no log rotation configured.</p>
    <p><strong>Permanent fix:</strong> Configure <code>logrotate</code> for the app. Set log level to INFO in production. Add disk space alerting at 80%.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="incident">
    <div class="incident-label">🚨 Production Incident — Simulation</div>
    <h4>Permission Denied After Deployment</h4>
    <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> New deployment works on staging, fails on prod with permission denied on config file.</p>
    <p><strong>Investigation:</strong></p>
    <pre style="margin:8px 0"><code><span class="cn">namei</span> <span class="fl">-l</span> <span class="st">/etc/myapp/config.json</span>
<span class="cm"># drwxr-xr-x root   root /</span>
<span class="cm"># drwxr-xr-x root   root etc</span>
<span class="cm"># drwx------ root   root myapp   ← PROBLEM: directory is 700, not 750</span>
<span class="cm"># -rw-r----- root   myapp config.json</span></code></pre>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> <code>chmod 750 /etc/myapp</code> — the app user is in the <code>myapp</code> group but the directory had no group execute bit.</p>
    <p><strong>Lesson:</strong> Always use <code>namei -l</code> for permission debugging. The problem is often a parent directory, not the file itself.</p>
  </div>
