    <h4>How a senior engineer thinks about the filesystem</h4>
    <p style="color:var(--text2); font-size:14px; line-height:1.75;">The filesystem is not just storage — it is the OS's interface. Senior engineers know that <strong style="color:var(--text)">/proc and /sys are the kernel speaking to you</strong> in real time. They reach for <code>namei -l</code> before assuming a permission is wrong. They always run <code>df -i</code> alongside <code>df -h</code>. They know that <code>mv</code> within one partition is atomic (a rename syscall), making it safe for deployment swaps, while <code>mv</code> across partitions is a copy+delete that can leave partial files on crash. They design application directories defensively — correct minimal permissions, SetGID for shared team directories, no world-writable paths. And they never, ever run a recursive operation without checking the path first.</p>
